      <h2>How Sous Vide Works</h2>
      <p>Sous vide, which translates to "under vacuum" in French, is a cooking method where food is placed in a plastic pouch or a glass jar and cooked in a water bath for longer than normal cooking times (usually 1 to 72 hours) at an accurately regulated temperature.</p>
      <p>The temperature is much lower than normally used for cooking, typically around 130°F to 140°F (55°C to 60°C) for meat, higher for vegetables. The intent is to cook the item evenly, ensuring that the inside is properly cooked without overcooking the outside, and to retain moisture.</p>

      <h2>Essential Equipment</h2>
      <div class="guide-grid">
        <div class="guide-box">
          <h3>Immersion Circulators</h3>
          <p>This is the core of your sous vide setup. A stick-like device that heats the water and circulates it to maintain an extremely precise temperature throughout the bath.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-box">
          <h3>Containers</h3>
          <p>While any large pot works, polycarbonate containers are ideal. They are transparent, hold temperature well, and have straight sides for maximizing space.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-box">
          <h3>Bags</h3>
          <p>You can use specialized vacuum sealer bags, but heavy-duty zip-top freezer bags are perfectly fine using the water-displacement method to remove air.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-box">
          <h3>Vacuum Sealer (Optional)</h3>
          <p>While not strictly necessary for most cooks, a vacuum sealer removes air perfectly and ensures bags won't float or leak during long cooks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
