    <div class="content">
      <h2>Finishing Techniques</h2>
      <p>Because sous vide cooks food in a very humid environment, it will not develop a crust or brown exterior. To achieve this, you need a finishing step.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pan Searing:</strong> Use a very hot cast-iron skillet with a high-smoke-point oil (like avocado or grapeseed). Sear the meat for just 30-60 seconds per side to prevent overcooking the interior.</li>
        <li><strong>Kitchen Torch:</strong> A powerful culinary torch is excellent for odd-shaped meats or finishing food extremely quickly without heating the interior.</li>
        <li><strong>Broiling:</strong> Good for larger items or multiple items at once. Ensure your broiler is fully preheated before placing the food under it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Safety & Pasteurization</h2>
      <p>Safety is a common concern due to the lower cooking temperatures. However, food safety is a function of both temperature and time. Cooking a chicken breast at 140°F (60°C) is perfectly safe if held at that temperature for an extended period, which pasteurizes the meat. Always refer to established safety charts for precise pasteurization times for specific temperatures.</p>

      <h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Floating Bags:</strong> If a bag has air in it, it will float, resulting in uneven cooking. Ensure bags are fully submerged. Weigh them down if necessary.</li>
        <li><strong>Not Drying Before Searing:</strong> Moisture is the enemy of a good sear. Always pat your meat completely dry with paper towels before hitting the pan.</li>
        <li><strong>Cooking Too Long:</strong> While you won't overcook by temperature, extending cooking times by many hours can turn meat excessively mushy or mealy.</li>
        <li><strong>Crowding the Bath:</strong> Ensure there is enough space between bags for water to circulate. If bags are tightly packed, the food may not reach the target temperature evenly.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">What is sous vide cooking?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Sous vide is a method of cooking where food is vacuum-sealed in a bag and placed in a water bath with a precisely regulated temperature. This ensures even cooking and prevents overcooking.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Do I need a vacuum sealer for sous vide?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">No, you don't strictly need a vacuum sealer. You can use food-grade resealable bags and the "water displacement method" by submerging the bag in water to push the air out before sealing it.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Is it safe to cook in plastic bags?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes, as long as you use food-grade, BPA-free plastic bags designed for cooking, such as high-quality freezer bags or specialized sous vide vacuum bags.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Can I overcook food with sous vide?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">While it is very difficult to overcook food in terms of temperature (a steak will never go above the water bath's temperature), leaving food in the bath for way too long can cause the texture to become mushy.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Why do I need to sear meat after sous vide cooking?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Sous vide cooks the food perfectly inside, but the exterior will lack the appealing crust and flavor created by the Maillard reaction. Searing the food quickly in a hot pan or with a torch adds this crucial texture and flavor.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
